{"author":{"id":"e67399cd878a39f357fb779b1874807d4611a3675cae056f8453faca8ed62477"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1780002979,"nonce":"23w8z1rqgwjghtclEWtxu2hgIdk=","message":"Fixed in daacaa5 (\"Make TUI packages importable without the textual extra\").\n\nRoot cause: `b4/review_tui/__init__.py` and `b4/tui/__init__.py` were doing\neager `from b4.review_tui._common import ...` style re-exports at package\nload time, and the submodules behind those imports call\n`from textual.app import ComposeResult` etc. at the top of the file. So\njust `import b4.review_tui` -- which is what Fedora's\n`import_all_modules.py` post-install check does -- pulls in `textual`,\neven though the actual TUI code paths are guarded with `try/except\nImportError` in the relevant `cmd_tui` entry points.\n\nFix: convert both package `__init__.py` files to PEP 562 lazy attribute\naccess (`__getattr__`). The bare `import b4.review_tui` / `import b4.tui`\nnow succeeds without `textual` installed; only attribute access (e.g.\n`b4.review_tui.run_tracking_tui`) triggers the actual textual-dependent\nsubmodule import. `TYPE_CHECKING` imports keep the public API visible to\nmypy/pyright/ty so static analysis is unchanged.\n\nThe one in-tree caller that obtained the package via\n`import b4.review_tui as review_tui` was switched to\n`from b4.review_tui._entry import run_tracking_tui` inside its existing\ntry/except guard, so the user-facing \"install b4[tui]\" message keeps\nfiring when the extra is missing.\n\nAdded `src/tests/test_packaging.py` as a regression test: spawns a\nsubprocess, blocks `textual` via `sys.meta_path`, then uses\n`pkgutil.walk_packages` to import every public `b4.*` submodule -- same\nmechanism downstream packagers use, so any new TUI-leaking module we add\nlater is automatically covered.\n\nThis will land in the 0.16 release. Will also be eligible for a 0.15.x\npoint release if a backport is wanted for Fedora packaging in the\nmeantime.","files":null}]}